<section xml:id="review-pfd">
	<title>Partial Fraction Decomposition</title>

	<p>
		Partial fraction decomposition is a method used to express a rational function as a sum of simpler fractions. This process is especially useful when solving integrals and applying inverse Laplace transforms. The following steps outline the process to find the partial fraction decomposition of a rational function.
	</p>
	
	<dl width="narrow">
		<li><title>Check the Degree of the Numerator and Denominator</title>
			<p>
				Ensure the degree of the numerator is less than the degree of the denominator. If the numerator has a degree greater than or equal to the denominator, first perform polynomial long division to reduce the degree of the numerator.
			</p>
		</li>
		<li><title>Factor the Denominator</title>
			<p>
				Factor the denominator into irreducible linear or quadratic factors.
				<ul marker="square">
					<li>
						<term>Linear factors:</term> Expressions of the form <m>(s - a)</m>.
					</li>
					<li>
						<term>Irreducible quadratic factors:</term> Expressions of the form <m>(s^2 + bs + c)</m> where the discriminant <m>b^2 - 4ac</m> is negative.
					</li>
				</ul>
			</p>
		</li>
		<li><title>Set up the Partial Fraction Decomposition</title>
			<p>
				Based on the factors of the denominator, write the decomposition:
				<ul marker="square">
					<li>
						For each linear factor <m>(s - a)</m>, include a term of the form <me>\frac{A}{s - a}</me>.
					</li>
					<li>
						For repeated linear factors <m>(s - a)^n</m>, include terms like:
						<me>
							\frac{A_1}{s - a} + \frac{A_2}{(s - a)^2} + \dots + \frac{A_n}{(s - a)^n}.
						</me>
					</li>
					<li>
						For irreducible quadratic factors <m>(s^2 + bs + c)</m>, include a term of the form <me>\frac{Bs + C}{s^2 + bs + c}</me>.
					</li>
					<li>
						For repeated quadratic factors <m>(s^2 + bs + c)^n</m>, include terms like:
						<me>
							\frac{B_1s + C_1}{s^2 + bs + c} + \frac{B_2s + C_2}{(s^2 + bs + c)^2} + \dots + \frac{B_ns + C_n}{(s^2 + bs + c)^n}.
						</me>
					</li>
				</ul>
			</p>
		</li>
		<li><title>Solve for the Constants</title>
			<p>
				Multiply both sides of the equation by the common denominator and expand to eliminate fractions. Group terms by powers of <m>s</m> and set up a system of equations to solve for the unknown constants <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>.
			</p>
		</li>
		<li><title>Final Result</title>
			<p>
				Once the constants are found, write the final partial fraction decomposition. This decomposition can now be used for further calculations such as integrals or inverse Laplace transforms.
			</p>
		</li>
	</dl>
	
	<assemblage xml:id="partial-fraction-table"><title>✳️ Reference: Partial Fraction General Form Terms</title>

		<p>
			For each type of factor in the denominator, add the following terms to the partial fraction decomposition:
		</p>

		<p>
			<sidebyside widths="20% 25% 55%">
				<p><term>Factor Type</term></p>
				<p><term>Factor</term></p>
				<p><term>Term(s) In General Form</term></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="20% 25% 55%">
				<p><term>Linear</term></p>
				<p><m>(s - a)</m></p>
				<p><m>\ds\frac{A}{s - a}</m></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="20% 25% 55%">
				<p><term>Repeated Linear</term></p>
				<p><m>(s - a)^n</m></p>
				<p><m>\ds\frac{A_1}{s - a} + \frac{A_2}{(s - a)^2} + \dots + \frac{A_n}{(s - a)^n}</m></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="20% 25% 55%">
				<p><term>Irreducible Quadratic</term></p>
				<p><m>(s^2 + bs + c)</m></p>
				<p><m>\ds\frac{Bs + C}{s^2 + bs + c}</m></p>
			</sidebyside>
			<sidebyside widths="20% 25% 55%">
				<p><term>Repeated Quadratic</term></p>
				<p><m>(s^2 + bs + c)^n</m></p>
				<p><m>\ds\frac{B_1s + C_1}{s^2 + bs + c} + \dots + \frac{B_ns + C_n}{(s^2 + bs + c)^n}</m></p>
			</sidebyside>
		</p>
	</assemblage>

	<example>
		<p>
			 Find the partial fraction decomposition form for each.
		</p>
		<ol>
			<li>
				<m>\ds\frac{8x^2 - 51x + 41}{x^2 - 6x + 5}</m>
				<solution>
					<p>
						First, check the degrees: the numerator and denominator both have degree <m>2</m>, so this rational function is <em>improper</em> and we must divide before decomposing. Polynomial long division gives
						<me>
							\frac{8x^2 - 51x + 41}{x^2 - 6x + 5} = 8 + \frac{-3x + 1}{x^2 - 6x + 5}.
						</me>
						Next, factor the denominator:
						<me>
							x^2 - 6x + 5 = (x - 5)(x - 1).
						</me>
						The denominator has the following factors:
						<ul marker="square">
							<li> <m>x-5</m> (linear, single) </li>
							<li> <m>x-1</m> (linear, single) </li>
						</ul>
						Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
						<me>
							u(x) = 8 + \frac{A}{x-5} + \frac{B}{x-1}.
						</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</li>
			<li>
				<m>\ds\frac{17x - 11}{x^2(x-3)} \qquad</m>		
				<solution>
					<p>
				Since the denominator is already factored, we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>x</m> (linear, double) </li>
						<li> <m>x-3</m> (linear, distinct) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> g(x) = \frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x^2} + \frac{C}{x-3}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</li>
			<li>
				<m>\ds\frac{x+12}{(x^2 - 4)^2} \qquad</m>		
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> h(x) = \frac{x+12}{(x^2 - 4)^2} = \frac{x+12}{[(x-2)(x+2)]^2} = \frac{x+12}{(x-2)^2(x+2)^2} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-2)</m> (linear, double) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+2)</m> (linear, double) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> h(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{(x-2)^2} + \frac{C}{x+2} + \frac{D}{(x+2)^2}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</li>
			<li>
				<m>\ds\frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x^2 + 2x + 1)} \qquad</m> 	
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> r(x) = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x^2 + 2x + 1)} = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x+1)(x+1)} = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)^3} </me>
					Now we see that <m>(x+1)</m> (which is linear), is a factor (three times) of the denominator.
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> r(x) = \frac{A}{x+1} + \frac{B}{(x+1)^2} + \frac{C}{(x+1)^3}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
			</li>
		</ol>
	</example>

	<example>
		<p>
			 Find the partial fraction decomposition of <me>\frac{5s + 4}{(s - 1)(s^2 + s + 1)}</me>.
		</p>
		<solution>
			<p>
				The numerator has smaller degree than the denominator, and the denominator is already factored into a linear factor <m>(s - 1)</m> and an irreducible quadratic factor <m>(s^2 + s + 1)</m> (its discriminant is <m>1 - 4 = -3 \lt 0</m>). So the partial fraction decomposition has the form:
				<me>
					\frac{5s + 4}{(s - 1)(s^2 + s + 1)} = \frac{A}{s - 1} + \frac{Bs + C}{s^2 + s + 1}.
				</me>
			</p>

			<p>
				Multiply through by <m>(s - 1)(s^2 + s + 1)</m> and expand:
				<md>
					<mrow> 5s + 4 \amp = A(s^2 + s + 1) + (Bs + C)(s - 1) </mrow>
					<mrow> \amp = (A + B)s^2 + (A - B + C)s + (A - C). </mrow>
				</md>
			</p>

			<p>
				Comparing coefficients of <m>s^2</m>, <m>s</m>, and the free terms gives the system:
				<me>
					A + B = 0, \quad A - B + C = 5, \quad A - C = 4
				</me>
				which has solution <m>A = 3</m>, <m>B = -3</m>, <m>C = -1</m>.
			</p>

			<p>
				Therefore, the partial fraction decomposition is:
				<me>
					\frac{5s + 4}{(s - 1)(s^2 + s + 1)} = \frac{3}{s - 1} - \frac{3s + 1}{s^2 + s + 1}.
				</me>
			</p>
		</solution>
	</example>

	<exercises>

		<exercisegroup cols="2"><title>General Form</title>
		
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Find the <em>FORM</em> of the partial fraction decomposition for each of the following. Make sure you completely factor each denominator before determining the decomposition. You need not find the values of the coefficients <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> etc.
				</p>
			</introduction>
		
			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds g(x) = \frac{17x - 11}{x^2(x-3)}</m>		
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Since the denominator is already factored, we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>x</m> (linear, double) </li>
						<li> <m>x-3</m> (linear, distinct) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> g(x) = \frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x^2} + \frac{C}{x-3}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> g(x) = \frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x^2} + \frac{C}{x-3} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds h(x) = \frac{x+12}{(x^2 - 4)^2}</m>		
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> h(x) = \frac{x+12}{(x^2 - 4)^2} = \frac{x+12}{[(x-2)(x+2)]^2} = \frac{x+12}{(x-2)^2(x+2)^2} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-2)</m> (linear, double) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+2)</m> (linear, double) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> h(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{(x-2)^2} + \frac{C}{x+2} + \frac{D}{(x+2)^2}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> h(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{(x-2)^2} + \frac{C}{x+2} + \frac{D}{(x+2)^2} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds r(x) = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x^2 + 2x + 1)}</m> 	
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> r(x) = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x^2 + 2x + 1)} = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x+1)(x+1)} = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)^3} </me>
					Now we see that <m>(x+1)</m> (which is linear), is a factor (three times) of the denominator.
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> r(x) = \frac{A}{x+1} + \frac{B}{(x+1)^2} + \frac{C}{(x+1)^3}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> r(x) = \frac{A}{x+1} + \frac{B}{(x+1)^2} + \frac{C}{(x+1)^3} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds s(x) = \frac{111}{(x^2 - 9)(x^2+9)}</m>		
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> s(x) = \frac{111}{(x^2 - 9)(x^2+9)} = \frac{111}{(x-3)(x+3)(x^2 + 9)} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-3)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+3)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x^2 + 9)</m> (irreducible quadratic, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> s(x) = \frac{A}{x-3} + \frac{B}{x+3} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 9}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me>  s(x) = \frac{A}{x-3} + \frac{B}{x+3} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 9} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds t(x) = \frac{2x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4)}</m>		
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> t(x) = \frac{2x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4)} = \frac{2x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x-2)(x+2)(x^2 + 4)} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-2)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+2)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x^2 + 4)</m> (irreducible quadratic, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> t(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{x+2} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 4}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> t(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{x+2} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 4} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds u(x) = \frac{3x^2 - 2x + 1}{(x^2 - 1)(x^2 + 1)}</m>		
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> u(x) = \frac{3x^2 - 2x + 1}{(x^2 - 1)(x^2 + 1)} = \frac{3x^2 - 2x + 1}{(x-1)(x+1)(x^2 + 1)} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-1)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+1)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x^2 + 1)</m> (irreducible quadratic, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> u(x) = \frac{A}{x-1} + \frac{B}{x+1} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 1}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> u(x) = \frac{A}{x-1} + \frac{B}{x+1} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 1} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds v(x) = \frac{4x^2 - 5x + 2}{x^4 - 2x^2 + 1}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> v(x) = \frac{4x^2 - 5x + 2}{(x^2 - 1)^2} = \frac{4x^2 - 5x + 2}{[(x-1)(x+1)]^2} = \frac{4x^2 - 5x + 2}{(x-1)^2(x+1)^2} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-1)</m> (linear, double) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+1)</m> (linear, double) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> v(x) = \frac{A}{x-1} + \frac{B}{(x-1)^2} + \frac{C}{x+1} + \frac{D}{(x+1)^2}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> v(x) = \frac{A}{x-1} + \frac{B}{(x-1)^2} + \frac{C}{x+1} + \frac{D}{(x+1)^2} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds w(x) = \frac{5x^2 - 3x + 1}{x^4 - 16}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> w(x) = \frac{5x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4)} = \frac{5x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x-2)(x+2)(x^2 + 4)} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-2)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+2)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x^2 + 4)</m> (irreducible quadratic, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> w(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{x+2} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 4}. </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> w(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{x+2} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 4} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds p(x) = \frac{x^5 - 3x - 27}{x^3 - 2x^2 - 3x}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				First, check the degrees: the numerator has degree <m>5</m> and the denominator has degree <m>3</m>, so this rational function is improper and we must divide first. Polynomial long division gives
					<me>
						\frac{x^5 - 3x - 27}{x^3 - 2x^2 - 3x} = x^2 + 2x + 7 + \frac{20x^2 + 18x - 27}{x^3 - 2x^2 - 3x}.
					</me>
					Next, factor the denominator:
					<me>
						x^3 - 2x^2 - 3x = x(x^2 - 2x - 3) = x(x - 3)(x + 1).
					</me>
					The denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>x</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>x-3</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>x+1</m> (linear, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me>
						p(x) = x^2 + 2x + 7 + \frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x-3} + \frac{C}{x+1}.
					</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me>
							p(x) = x^2 + 2x + 7 + \frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x-3} + \frac{C}{x+1}
						</me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds q(x) = \frac{8x^2 - 51x + 41}{x^2 - 6x + 5}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				First, check the degrees: the numerator and denominator both have degree <m>2</m>, so this rational function is improper and we must divide first. Polynomial long division gives
					<me>
						\frac{8x^2 - 51x + 41}{x^2 - 6x + 5} = 8 + \frac{-3x + 1}{x^2 - 6x + 5}.
					</me>
					Next, factor the denominator:
					<me>
						x^2 - 6x + 5 = (x - 5)(x - 1).
					</me>
					The denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>x-5</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>x-1</m> (linear, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me>
						q(x) = 8 + \frac{A}{x-5} + \frac{B}{x-1}.
					</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me>
							q(x) = 8 + \frac{A}{x-5} + \frac{B}{x-1}
						</me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>
		
		</exercisegroup>

		<exercisegroup cols="2"><title>Partial Fraction Decomposition</title>
		
			<introduction>
				<p>
					Find the partial fraction decomposition for each of the following rational functions.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds f(x) = \frac{3x^2 - 2x + 1}{x^3 - 2x^2 - 3x}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				First, factor the denominator:
					<me>
						x^3 - 2x^2 - 3x = x(x^2 - 2x - 3) = x(x - 3)(x + 1).
					</me>
					The denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>x</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>x-3</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>x+1</m> (linear, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me>
						f(x) = \frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x-3} + \frac{C}{x+1}.
					</me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> and <m>C.</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me>
							f(x) = -\frac{1}{3x} + \frac{11}{6(x-3)} + \frac{3}{2(x+1)}
						</me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds g(x) = \frac{17x - 11}{x^2(x-3)}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Since the denominator is already factored, we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>x</m> (linear, double) </li>
						<li> <m>x-3</m> (linear, distinct) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> g(x) = \frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x^2} + \frac{C}{x-3}. </me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> and <m>C.</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> g(x) = -\frac{40}{9x} + \frac{11}{3x^2} + \frac{40}{9(x-3)} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds h(x) = \frac{x+12}{(x^2 - 4)^2}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> h(x) = \frac{x+12}{(x^2 - 4)^2} = \frac{x+12}{[(x-2)(x+2)]^2} = \frac{x+12}{(x-2)^2(x+2)^2} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-2)</m> (linear, double) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+2)</m> (linear, double) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> h(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{(x-2)^2} + \frac{C}{x+2} + \frac{D}{(x+2)^2}. </me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> <m>C,</m> and <m>D.</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> h(x) = -\frac{3}{8(x-2)} + \frac{7}{8(x-2)^2} + \frac{3}{8(x+2)} + \frac{5}{8(x+2)^2} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds r(x) = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x^2 + 2x + 1)}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> r(x) = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x^2 + 2x + 1)} = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)(x+1)(x+1)} = \frac{3x-14}{(x+1)^3} </me>
					Now we see that <m>(x+1)</m> (which is linear), is a factor (three times) of the denominator.
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> r(x) = \frac{A}{x+1} + \frac{B}{(x+1)^2} + \frac{C}{(x+1)^3}. </me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> and <m>C.</m> Note that solving gives <m>A = 0</m> here, so the <m>\frac{A}{x+1}</m> term drops out of the final decomposition.
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> r(x) = \frac{3}{(x+1)^2} - \frac{17}{(x+1)^3} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds s(x) = \frac{111}{(x^2 - 9)(x^2+9)}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> s(x) = \frac{111}{(x^2 - 9)(x^2+9)} = \frac{111}{(x-3)(x+3)(x^2 + 9)} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-3)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+3)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x^2 + 9)</m> (irreducible quadratic, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> s(x) = \frac{A}{x-3} + \frac{B}{x+3} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 9}. </me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> <m>C,</m> and <m>D.</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> s(x) = \frac{37}{36(x-3)} - \frac{37}{36(x+3)} - \frac{37}{6(x^2 + 9)} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds t(x) = \frac{2x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4)}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> t(x) = \frac{2x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4)} = \frac{2x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x-2)(x+2)(x^2 + 4)} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-2)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+2)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x^2 + 4)</m> (irreducible quadratic, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> t(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{x+2} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 4}. </me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> <m>C,</m> and <m>D.</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> t(x) = \frac{3}{32(x-2)} - \frac{15}{32(x+2)} + \frac{3x + 7}{8(x^2 + 4)} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>

			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds u(x) = \frac{3x^2 - 2x + 1}{(x^2 - 1)(x^2 + 1)}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> u(x) = \frac{3x^2 - 2x + 1}{(x^2 - 1)(x^2 + 1)} = \frac{3x^2 - 2x + 1}{(x-1)(x+1)(x^2 + 1)} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-1)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+1)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x^2 + 1)</m> (irreducible quadratic, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> u(x) = \frac{A}{x-1} + \frac{B}{x+1} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 1}. </me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> <m>C,</m> and <m>D.</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> u(x) = \frac{1}{2(x-1)} - \frac{3}{2(x+1)} + \frac{x + 1}{x^2 + 1} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds v(x) = \frac{4x^2 - 5x + 2}{x^4 - 2x^2 + 1}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> v(x) = \frac{4x^2 - 5x + 2}{(x^2 - 1)^2} = \frac{4x^2 - 5x + 2}{[(x-1)(x+1)]^2} = \frac{4x^2 - 5x + 2}{(x-1)^2(x+1)^2} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-1)</m> (linear, double) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+1)</m> (linear, double) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> v(x) = \frac{A}{x-1} + \frac{B}{(x-1)^2} + \frac{C}{x+1} + \frac{D}{(x+1)^2}. </me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> <m>C,</m> and <m>D.</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> v(x) = \frac{1}{2(x-1)} + \frac{1}{4(x-1)^2} - \frac{1}{2(x+1)} + \frac{11}{4(x+1)^2} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>\ds w(x) = \frac{5x^2 - 3x + 1}{x^4 - 16}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Here we need to finish factoring the denominator:
					<me> w(x) = \frac{5x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4)} = \frac{5x^2 - 3x + 1}{(x-2)(x+2)(x^2 + 4)} </me>
					Now we see that the denominator has the following factors:
					<ul marker="square">
						<li> <m>(x-2)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x+2)</m> (linear, single) </li>
						<li> <m>(x^2 + 4)</m> (irreducible quadratic, single) </li>
					</ul>
					Hence, the FORM of the partial fraction decomposition is:
					<me> w(x) = \frac{A}{x-2} + \frac{B}{x+2} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2 + 4}. </me>
					Multiply both sides by the common denominator and solve for <m>A,</m> <m>B,</m> <m>C,</m> and <m>D.</m>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> w(x) = \frac{15}{32(x-2)} - \frac{27}{32(x+2)} + \frac{3x + 19}{8(x^2 + 4)} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>g(x) = \ds \frac{1}{x^2 - 5x+6}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				<me>g(x) = \frac{1}{x^2 - 5x+6} = \frac{1}{(x-3)(x-2)} = \frac{A}{x-3} + \frac{B}{x-2}	</me>
					<md>
						<mrow>\frac{1}{(x-3)(x-2)}\cdot (x-3)(x-2) = \left[\frac{A}{x-3} + \frac{B}{x-2} \right] \cdot (x-3)(x-2)</mrow>
						<mrow>1 = A(x-2) + B(x-3)</mrow>
						<mrow>1 = Ax - 2A + Bx - 3B</mrow>
						<mrow>1 = (A+B)x + (-2A - 3B)</mrow>
					</md>
					<sidebyside widths="40% 10% 40%" margins="auto" valign="top">
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>A+B = 0</mrow>
								<mrow>B = -A</mrow>
								<mrow></mrow>
							</md>
						</p>
						<p> and </p>
						<p>
							<md>
								<mrow>-2A - 3B = 1</mrow>
								<mrow>-2A - 3(-A) = 1</mrow>
								<mrow>A = 1</mrow>
							</md>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
					<me> B = -A = -1 </me>
					<me>  \Rightarrow g(x) = \frac{1}{x-3} + \frac{-1}{x-2}</me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> g(x) = \frac{1}{x-3} + \frac{-1}{x-2} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>h(x) = \ds \frac{4x+7}{x^2 - 7x}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				<md>
						<mrow>h(x) = \frac{4x+7}{x^2 - 7x} = \frac{4x+7}{x(x-7)}</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{4x+7}{x(x-7)} = \frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x-7}</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{4x+7}{x(x-7)}\cdot x(x-7) = \left[\frac{A}{x} + \frac{B}{x-7}\right] \cdot x(x-7)</mrow>
						<mrow>4x+7 = A(x-7) + Bx</mrow>
						<mrow>4x+7 = Ax - 7A + Bx</mrow>
						<mrow>4x+7 = (A+B)x + (-7A)</mrow>
					</md>
					<md>
						<mrow>\Rightarrow A+B = 4 \amp\text{and }	</mrow>
						<mrow>-7A = 7</mrow>
						<mrow> \amp	\amp A = -1</mrow>
						<mrow>(-1)+B = 4 \amp		\amp	</mrow>
						<mrow>B = 5 \amp		\amp	</mrow>
					</md>
					<me> \Rightarrow h(x) = \frac{-1}{x} + \frac{5}{x-7} </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> h(x) = \frac{-1}{x} + \frac{5}{x-7} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>r(x) = \ds \frac{20x^2+65x+115}{(x^2+9)(x+11)}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				<md>
						<mrow>\frac{20x^2+65x+115}{(x^2+9)(x+11)} = \frac{A}{x+11} + \frac{Bx+C}{x^2+9}</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{20x^2+65x+115}{(x^2+9)(x+11)}\cdot (x^2+9)(x+11) = \left[\frac{A}{x+11} + \frac{Bx+C}{x^2+9}\right] \cdot (x^2+9)(x+11)</mrow>
						<mrow>20x^2+65x+115 = A(x^2+9) + (Bx+C)(x+11)</mrow>
						<mrow>20x^2+65x+115 = Ax^2+9A + Bx^2+11Bx + Cx+11C</mrow>
						<mrow>20x^2+65x+115 = (A+B)x^2 + (11B+C)x + 9A+11C</mrow>
					</md>
					Matching coefficients gives the system
					<md>
						<mrow>A+B \amp = 20</mrow>
						<mrow>11B+C \amp = 65</mrow>
						<mrow>9A+11C \amp = 115</mrow>
					</md>
					From the first equation, <m>B = 20 - A</m>. Substituting into the second, <m>C = 65 - 11(20-A) = 11A - 155</m>. Substituting both into the third:
					<md>
						<mrow>9A + 11(11A - 155) \amp = 115</mrow>
						<mrow>130A \amp = 1820</mrow>
						<mrow>A \amp = 14</mrow>
					</md>
					so <m>B = 20 - 14 = 6</m> and <m>C = 11(14) - 155 = -1</m>.
					<me> \Rightarrow r(x) = \frac{14}{x+11} + \frac{6x-1}{x^2+9} </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> r(x) = \frac{14}{x+11} + \frac{6x-1}{x^2+9} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>s(x) = \ds \frac{3x^2+5x+7}{(x^2+4)(x^2+16)}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Both factors are irreducible quadratics, so each contributes a term with a <em>linear</em> numerator:
				<md>
						<mrow>\frac{3x^2+5x+7}{(x^2+4)(x^2+16)} = \frac{Ax+B}{x^2+4} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2+16}</mrow>
						<mrow>3x^2+5x+7 = (Ax+B)(x^2+16) + (Cx+D)(x^2+4)</mrow>
						<mrow>3x^2+5x+7 = (A+C)x^3 + (B+D)x^2 + (16A+4C)x + (16B+4D)</mrow>
					</md>
					Matching coefficients gives the system
					<md>
						<mrow>A+C \amp = 0</mrow>
						<mrow>B+D \amp = 3</mrow>
						<mrow>16A+4C \amp = 5</mrow>
						<mrow>16B+4D \amp = 7</mrow>
					</md>
					From the first equation, <m>C = -A</m>, so <m>16A - 4A = 5</m> gives <m>A = \frac{5}{12}</m> and <m>C = -\frac{5}{12}</m>. From the second, <m>D = 3 - B</m>, so <m>16B + 4(3-B) = 7</m> gives <m>B = -\frac{5}{12}</m> and <m>D = \frac{41}{12}</m>.
					<me> \Rightarrow s(x) = \frac{5x-5}{12(x^2+4)} + \frac{-5x+41}{12(x^2+16)} </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> s(x) = \frac{5x-5}{12(x^2+4)} + \frac{-5x+41}{12(x^2+16)} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>

			<exercise>
				<statement>
					<p>
						<m>t(x) = \ds \frac{2x^2+3x+5}{(x^2+1)(x^2+4)}</m>
					</p>
				</statement>
				<solution>
					<p>
				Both factors are irreducible quadratics, so each contributes a term with a <em>linear</em> numerator:
				<md>
						<mrow>\frac{2x^2+3x+5}{(x^2+1)(x^2+4)} = \frac{Ax+B}{x^2+1} + \frac{Cx+D}{x^2+4}</mrow>
						<mrow>2x^2+3x+5 = (Ax+B)(x^2+4) + (Cx+D)(x^2+1)</mrow>
						<mrow>2x^2+3x+5 = (A+C)x^3 + (B+D)x^2 + (4A+C)x + (4B+D)</mrow>
					</md>
					Matching coefficients gives the system
					<md>
						<mrow>A+C \amp = 0</mrow>
						<mrow>B+D \amp = 2</mrow>
						<mrow>4A+C \amp = 3</mrow>
						<mrow>4B+D \amp = 5</mrow>
					</md>
					Subtracting the first equation from the third gives <m>3A = 3</m>, so <m>A = 1</m> and <m>C = -1</m>. Subtracting the second from the fourth gives <m>3B = 3</m>, so <m>B = 1</m> and <m>D = 1</m>.
					<me> \Rightarrow t(x) = \frac{x+1}{x^2+1} + \frac{-x+1}{x^2+4} </me>
					</p>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<p>
						<me> t(x) = \frac{x+1}{x^2+1} + \frac{-x+1}{x^2+4} </me>
					</p>
				</answer>
			</exercise>
		
		</exercisegroup>
		
	</exercises>
</section>
